== 6. Common Interventions Parents Decline

Here are interventions that parents frequently choose to decline or modify:

=== Vitamin K Injection
- _Why parents decline:_ Concerns about synthetic ingredients, aluminum adjuvants in some formulations, pain of injection, preference for natural approaches
- _Alternatives:_ Oral vitamin K (not routinely offered in U.S. hospitals but available in other countries), dietary vitamin K through maternal diet and breastfeeding
- _What to know:_ Oral vitamin K requires multiple doses and has lower efficacy than injection for preventing late-onset bleeding

_For comprehensive details, see #link(<ch-vitamin-k>)[Chapter: Vitamin K]._

=== Hepatitis B Vaccine at Birth
- _Why parents decline:_ Mother is hepatitis B negative, prefer to delay vaccines, want to space out interventions, concerns about vaccine ingredients
- _Alternatives:_ Delayed hepatitis B vaccine at 2 months or 6 months, assessing actual risk factors
- _What to know:_ CDC strongly recommends for all babies at birth regardless of mother's status, but actual risk for babies born to hepatitis B negative mothers is extremely low

_For comprehensive details, see #link(<ch-hepatitis-b>)[Chapter: Hepatitis B Vaccine]._

=== Erythromycin Eye Ointment
- _Why parents decline:_ Mother tested negative for STIs, ointment can blur baby's vision during critical bonding window, prefer to avoid antibiotics unless indicated
- _Alternatives:_ Documented negative STI testing, visual observation for signs of infection
- _What to know:_ Some states legally require this, though enforcement varies. Newborn eye infections are rare but serious if they occur

_For comprehensive details, see #link(<ch-eye-ointment>)[Chapter: Eye Ointment]._

=== Circumcision
- _Why parents decline:_ No medical necessity, concerns about pain, prefer bodily autonomy, cultural or personal reasons
- _Alternatives:_ None; this is a permanent surgical decision
- _What to know:_ AAP says benefits and risks are roughly balanced, decision left to parents. Increasingly common to decline.

_For comprehensive details, see #link(<ch-circumcision>)[Chapter: Circumcision]._

=== Continuous Fetal Monitoring
- _Why parents decline:_ Restricts movement, increases cascade of interventions, high false-positive rate, intermittent monitoring has similar safety outcomes for low-risk births
- _Alternatives:_ Intermittent auscultation (listening to baby's heartbeat every 15-30 minutes)
- _What to know:_ Continuous monitoring is routine in U.S. hospitals despite evidence that intermittent monitoring is equally safe for low-risk pregnancies

_For comprehensive details, see #link(<ch-fetal-monitoring>)[Chapter: Fetal Monitoring]._

=== IV Fluids
- _Why parents decline:_ Want mobility, prefer to drink fluids orally, want to avoid unnecessary medical interventions
- _Alternatives:_ Hep lock (IV port without fluids running), no IV at all with commitment to oral hydration
- _What to know:_ IV is routine in hospitals but not medically necessary for low-risk labors. Oral hydration is sufficient.

=== Induction Without Medical Indication
- _Why parents decline:_ Prefer spontaneous labor, concern about cascade of interventions, want to avoid Pitocin
- _Alternatives:_ Expectant management (waiting for spontaneous labor), natural induction methods
- _What to know:_ Elective induction before 41 weeks (without medical indication) is increasingly common but increases intervention rates

_For comprehensive details, see #link(<ch-pitocin>)[Chapter: Pitocin]._

=== Routine Newborn Procedures During Golden Hour
- _Why parents decline:_ Want uninterrupted bonding time, prefer delayed procedures, want to establish breastfeeding
- _Alternatives:_ Delaying non-urgent procedures for 1-2 hours while baby is skin-to-skin
- _What to know:_ Most newborn procedures (weighing, measuring, bathing) can safely wait. True emergencies are obvious.

_For comprehensive details, see #link(<ch-skin-to-skin>)[Chapter: Skin-to-Skin Contact] and #link(<ch-first-bath>)[Chapter: First Bath]._

